PRESIDENT Jacob Zuma and Police Minister Fikile Mbalula visited a village at the weekend.They spoke to residents at an imbizo in Palmerton Village, Lusikisiki, Eastern Cape.Residents told the leaders they lived in fear because of the amaVondo gang.They said a number of incidents had been reported in Lusikisiki of young men who allegedly targeted FET students, killing them and drinking their blood!&ldquo;Police do their part and arrest these boys, but then they are released into the care of their parents because they are underage,&rdquo; said a resident. &ldquo;But they soon go back to their bad behaviour, attacking and killing people. This has stop. Enough is enough!&rdquo; Mbalula assured residents the provincial and national commissioners he brought with him would help fight crime.&ldquo;We will not be defeated by these boys. Cops thought amaVondo was just witchcraft, but they need special intelligence because crime is crime,&rdquo; said Mbalula. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s why the new police station in the area has all units, from intelligence to a K9 unit, tactical response and public order, among others.&rdquo; Zuma said: &ldquo;Provincial officials will meet their national counterparts and plan a way forward to address the residents&rsquo; issues.&rdquo;He was accompanied by Eastern Cape Premier Phumulo Masualle, King Zanozuko Sigcau and a number of ministers, deputy ministers and MECs.The visit was part of the president&rsquo;s siyahlola campaign.Zuma also visited St Elizabeth&rsquo;s Hospital.